quest_title: The number of 4 digit even numbers that can be formed using 0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6 without repetition is :
explanation_txt:
Last digit can be \(0,2,4,6\). [4 ways]

Second last digit can be: \(1,3,5 \) and 3 digits left from first place. [6 ways]

Similarly, third, fourth digits can be filled in 5 and 4 ways respectively.

This gives: \(N = 4 \times 6 \times 5 \times 4 = 480 \)

The numbers starting from 0, ending in even digits are: \(3 \times 5 \times 4 \times 1 = 60 \)

So, total number of valid numbers \( = 480-60 = 420 \)

quest_title: Which of the following will not change the pH if 1.0 ml of dilute HCl solution is added to
ans1_txt: 20 ml of the same dilute HCl solution
explanation_txt:
When an acid of normality \(N_1\) and volume \(V_1\) is mixed with another acid of normality \(N_2\) and volume \(V_2\), the resulting normality is:

\(N = \cfrac{N_1V_1 + N_2V_2}{V_1+V_2}\)

When neutral solution is added, \(N_2=0\)

So, \( N = \cfrac{N_1V_1}{V_1+V_2} \)

Hence, concentration decreases, and \(pH\) increases.

If \(N_1=N_2=N_a \)

\(N = \cfrac{N_a(V_1+V_2)}{V_1+V_2} = Na\)

So, for same \(pH\), the normality of two acids should be same.

quest_title: If the sum of three terms of G.P. is 19 and product is 216, then the common ratio of the series is
explanation_txt:
Let three terms of G.P. are \(a,\; ar,\; ar^{2} \).

Then \(a+ar+ar^{2} =19\)

\(\Rightarrow a[1+r+r^{2} ]=19 \quad (i) \)

\(a\; .\; ar\; .\; ar^{2} =216 \)

\( \Rightarrow a^{3} r^{3} =216 \)

\( \Rightarrow ar=6 \quad (ii) \)

Dividing each term of (i) by \(ar\) and then multiplying by \(6\) (in LHS)

\[\cfrac{6}{r} +\cfrac{6}{r} r+\cfrac{6}{r} r^{2} =19 \]

\[ \Rightarrow \cfrac{6}{r} +6+6r=19\]

\[ \Rightarrow r^{2} -\cfrac{13}{6} r+1=0\].

Hence \(r=\cfrac{3}{2} \).

quest_title: A car, starting from rest, accelerates at the rate \(f\) through a distance \(S ,\) then continues at constant speed for time \(t\) and then decelerates at the rate \(\cfrac { f } { 2 }\) to come to rest. If the total distance traversed is \(15 S ,\) then
explanation_txt:
Let car starts from point A from rest and moves up to point B with acceleration f.

Velocity of car at point B, \(v = \sqrt { 2 f S } \left[ \text { As } v ^ { 2 } = u ^ { 2 } + 2 a s \right]\)

Car moves distance BC with this constant velocity in time t.

\(x = \sqrt { 2 f S } . t \quad \ldots \text { (i) } [ \text { As } s = u t ]\)

So, the velocity of car at point C also will be \(\sqrt { 2 f s }\) and finally car stops after covering distance y.

\(\begin{aligned} \text { Distance } C D \Rightarrow y = \cfrac { ( \sqrt { 2 f S } ) ^ { 2 } } { 2 ( f / 2 ) } & = \cfrac { 2 f S } { f } = 2 S \\ \left[ \text { As } v ^ { 2 } \right. & = u ^ { 2 } - 2 a s \Rightarrow s = u ^ { 2 } / 2 a ] \end{aligned}\)

\(\begin{array} { l } { \text { So, the total distance } A D = A B + B C + C D = 15 S ( \text { given } ) } \\ { \Rightarrow \quad S + x + 2 S = 15 S \Rightarrow x = 12 S } \end{array}\)

Substituting the value of x in equation (i), we get

\(\begin{array} { l } { x = \sqrt { 2 f S } \cdot t \Rightarrow 12 S = \sqrt { 2 f S } . t \Rightarrow 144 S ^ { 2 } = 2 f S \cdot t ^ { 2 } } \\ { \Rightarrow S = \cfrac { 1 } { 72 } f t ^ { 2 } } \end{array}\)

quest_title: A constant force resisting the motion of car of mass 1500 kg is equal to one fifteenth of its weight. When travelling at 48 km/hr, the car is brought to rest in a distance of 50 m by applying brakes the additional retarding force due to brake is
explanation_txt:
\(\begin{aligned} F_{f}=& \cfrac{1}{15} \text { of } m g=\cfrac{1}{15} \times 15000=1000 \mathrm{N} \\ & v^{2}=u^{2}+2 a s \end{aligned}\)

or, \(a=-\cfrac{u^{2}}{2 s}=-\left(\cfrac{48000}{3600}\right)^{2} \times \cfrac{1}{2 \times 50}\)
\(\quad a=-\cfrac{u^{2}}{2 s}=-1.77 \mathrm{m} / \mathrm{s}^{2}\)
\(\quad F_{R}=m a=1500 \times 1.77=2666 \mathrm{N}\)

Now, \(F_{f}+F=F_{R}\)

\(\therefore F=2666-1000=1666 \mathrm{N}\)

quest_title: If M is the atomic mass and A is the mass number, packing fraction is given by
explanation_txt:
The mass of a nucleus is always less than the sum of masses of the nucleons constituting it. Packing fraction is a parameter to measure the deviation of the masses of nuclei and its constituents particles i.e nucleons.

Packing fraction \(= \cfrac { M - A } { A }\)

It measures the stability of the nucleus. Smaller the value of packing fraction, higher is the stability of nucleus.
